In other words, P is the set of all sets, no matter what they contain or whether they're members of themselves or not. The key difference between ∊ and P is that ∊ is a set that satisfies a specific condition (x ∉ x), whereas P is simply a collection of all sets, without any additional constraints. So, while ∊ is a set that's trying to be clever and exclude itself, P is just a humble set that accepts all sets, regardless of their properties.

